inbounds and nuw). In the provided reproducer, the source program is defined, but
the transformed target program becomes less defined: Alive2 shows that for a
specific pointer value (%ptr pointing just before a 1-byte non-local block), the
source computes a non-inbounds GEP first (landing inside the block), then
proceeds with an inbounds GEP from the valid pointer onward. The target
transformation incorrectly applies inbounds to the newly created GEP using a PHI
base that can be out-of-bounds, triggering poison/UB when the load is
attempted.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first transformation is performed by
InstCombinerImpl::foldPHIArgGEPIntoPHI.\n- The log shows: Old PHI of two GEPs is
replaced with a phi of base (%ptr.pn) and a single GEP with \"inbounds nuw\"
flags: \"%.pn = getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %ptr.pn, i64 1\".\n- However,
the first incoming GEP (%add.ptr) in the source had no inbounds flags, while the
second (%incdec.ptr) did have inbounds nuw.\n- Alive2 demonstrates that the
target introduces UB because the new inbounds GEP is applied to a base pointer
(%ptr.pn) that can be out-of-bounds on one incoming edge (the %ptr edge). In
contrast, the source first moved the pointer into bounds with a non-inbounds GEP,
then only used inbounds when the pointer was already in-bounds.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nThe implementation initializes GEPNoWrapFlags NW to
GEPNoWrapFlags::all() and then ANDs it only with the flags of the GEPs from
PN.incoming_values() excluding the first one (it iterates over
drop_begin(PN.incoming_values())). As a result, NW ends up being the intersection
of the flags of all the subsequent GEPs, but ignores the first GEP's flags
entirely.\n\nIn the reproducer, the first GEP (%add.ptr) has no inbounds/nuw
flags, while the second GEP (%incdec.ptr) has inbounds nuw. Because NW starts as
\"all()\" and only intersects with the second's flags, NW stays as inbounds nuw.
The newly created GEP is therefore marked inbounds nuw, even though one of the
original GEPs was not inbounds. This unsoundly strengthens semantics and causes
UB in the target where the source was defined.\n\nThus, NW must include the flags
of the first GEP as well. The simplest and correct fix is to initialize NW with
FirstInst->getNoWrapFlags() instead of GEPNoWrapFlags::all(). Alternatively,
perform NW &= FirstInst->getNoWrapFlags() before the loop.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombinePHI.cpp\n- Line 548:
Change initialization of NW from \"GEPNoWrapFlags NW = GEPNoWrapFlags::all();\"
to \"GEPNoWrapFlags NW = FirstInst->getNoWrapFlags();\". This ensures the
intersection of flags across all incoming GEPs, including the first one.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nBy correctly including the no-wrap flags of the first GEP when
computing NW, the new GEP created by foldPHIArgGEPIntoPHI will only be marked
inbounds/nuw if all original incoming GEPs had those properties. This prevents
unsound strengthening and avoids introducing UB in cases like the reproducer,
restoring correctness of the transformation.",
  "test_traj": [
    "diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombinePHI.cpp
b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombinePHI.cpp\nindex
cb5c44730512..66e1dbc72e7a 100644\n---
a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombinePHI.cpp\n+++
b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombinePHI.cpp\n@@ -545,7 +545,9 @@
Instruction *InstCombinerImpl::foldPHIArgGEPIntoPHI(PHINode &PN) {\n   //
especially bad when the PHIs are in the header of a loop.\n   bool NeededPhi =
false;\n \n-  GEPNoWrapFlags NW = GEPNoWrapFlags::all();\n+  // Initialize NW
with the first incoming GEP's flags so we form the\n+  // intersection across all
incoming GEPs, including the first.\n+  GEPNoWrapFlags NW =
FirstInst->getNoWrapFlags();\n \n   // Scan to see if all operands are the same
opcode, and all have one user.\n   for (Value *V :
drop_begin(PN.incoming_values())) {\n"
  ]
